Phase 1: The UI/UX Redesign (Visual Overhaul)
Your current Tkinter interface functions well but looks like a legacy application. For a consumer music app, users expect a sleek, "Spotify-esque" aesthetic.

Recommendation: Switch to CustomTkinter Since you are already using Python/Tkinter, switching to CustomTkinter is the most efficient path. It wraps standard Tkinter widgets but renders them with modern, rounded corners, high-DPI scaling, and professional dark mode themes (matching Windows 11/10 natively).

1. The New "Dashboard" Layout
Instead of just tabs, move to a Sidebar Navigation layout. This is the industry standard for media apps.

Left Sidebar:

Logo: High-res branding at the top.

Navigation: "Dashboard," "Downloader," "Library," "Playlists," "Settings."

Status: A small "Suno Connected" green dot indicator.

Main Content Area: Dynamic frame that switches based on sidebar selection.

Bottom Player Bar: Persists across all screens (like Spotify).

2. Key UI Improvements
The Player: Move the player from a separate widget to a "sticky" bottom bar.

Left: Album art thumbnail (fetch this from metadata), Song Title, Artist.

Center: Play/Pause (Circle button), Skip, Previous, Seek slider.

Right: Volume slider, Format toggle (MP3/WAV).

The Library:

Replace the standard Treeview with a scrollable frame of "Song Cards" or a modern DataGrid.

Add "skeleton loading" (grey bars pulsing) while the library scans.

The Token Input (The Friction Point):

Currently, users have to dig into F12 Developer Tools. This is a high churn point for non-tech users.

Solution: Build a "Login Helper" popup. While you can't bypass the cookie requirement easily due to Captchas, you can add a button that opens a concise visual tutorial (GIF) inside the app showing exactly how to get the cookie.

Phase 2: Professional Installer (Moving away from portable EXE)
To run ads, you need a trusted installer. Users are wary of downloading random .exe files that trigger "Unknown Publisher" warnings.

Tool: Inno Setup This is the standard for Windows installers. It will wrap your PyInstaller output into a setup.exe.

Steps:

Icon: Ensure SunoSync.exe has a high-res .ico file.

Inno Setup Script: Create a .iss file. This script will:

Install the app to C:\Program Files\SunoSync.

Create a Desktop Shortcut and Start Menu entry.

Register an uninstaller in the Windows Control Panel.

(Optional) Associate .suno or specific file types if needed.

Why this matters for ads:

It looks professional.

It installs usually into "Program Files," avoiding permission issues in random folders.

It provides a clean uninstall method, which is a requirement for certification on some ad platforms.

Phase 3: Architecture Refinement
Your current architecture is solid (main.py, suno_downloader.py, etc.). However, to support the redesign and installer, we need to tweak a few things.

1. Configuration Storage (config_manager.py)
Currently, portable apps often save config files next to the EXE.

Change: When installed, the app cannot write to C:\Program Files.

Fix: Update config_manager.py to save settings and the database to %APPDATA%\SunoSync\.

